         <div type="translation" ana="#b1" xml:id="zoor0005.translation" corresp="#zoor0005.transcription">
            <p>Monument of Sibylla, (daughter) of Asclepiades, who died (at the age) of 9 years, in
               (the) year 229(?), on (the) .. (day) of (the) month Xanthikos(?) on [the day] of
               Jupiter ? (Thursday).</p>
         </div>
      </body>
      <back>
         <div type="commentary">
            <p>The inscription provides a date of the month of Xanthikos in the year 229 according
               the Era of the Province of Arabia, or March 22, 334 CE - April 20, 334 CE. The
               restoration of the year is uncertain. The tombstone is one of about 700 discovered in
               Byzantine Zoora, and is badly weathered. The majority of the Greek tombstones from
               this location have been identified as Christian. The inscription contains both
               orthographic and grammatical errors and is engraved in a round script. The age
               numeral is marked with a horizontal line above, while the word ἔτους and the year
               numeral are "crowned by two peculiar horizontal bars with endings in the form of a
               scroll" (attested once elsewhere in the collection). The letter-cutter provides the
               third declension genitive Ἀσκληπιάδους although it is actually a first declension
               name (nominative: Ἀσκληπιάδης) and therefore should read Ἀσκληπιάδου. μη(νί) is
               abbreviated with a small η above the μ. The author suggests a restoration containing
               the formula "θάρσει, οὐδεὶς ἀθάνατος" as spanning a final two lines which are not
               extant. The author indicates that the attestation of the name Σίβυλλα in two epitaphs
               in Zoora suggests that local presence of Sibyllic tradition. He also notes that the
               Ἀσκληπιάδης of the inscription was probably a member of the medical profession.</p>
         </div>
